	<h4>
		Things to do nearby
	</h4>

	<h5>
		<a href="http://www.artic.edu/visit" target="_blank">
			Art Institute of Chicago
		</a>
	</h5>
	<p>
		Check out the newly-built modern wing or see the older classics. Wave hello to Natalya’s office across the street on the 14th floor of the Motorola Building.
	</p>

	<h5>
		<a href="http://www.cityofchicago.org/city/en/depts/dca/supp_info/millennium_park_-artarchitecture.html" target="_blank">
			Cloud Gate (aka The Bean) & Millenium Park
		</a>
	</h5>
	<p>
		This infamous sculpture and the surrounding parks make up part of Chicago’s “Emerald Necklace” - a series of parks and recreational areas along Chicago’s lakefront that are always open to the public, per urban designer/architect Daniel Burnham’s vision. If it is hot outside, be sure to see the spitting faces, known as Crown Fountain.
	</p>


	<h5>
		<a href="http://www.transitchicago.com/" target="_blank">CTA train in the Loop</a>
	</h5>
	<p>
		For a quick and cheap way to see the city, take a ride on the ‘L’ around the Loop on the Brown, Green, Pink, or Orange lines.
	</p>
	<h5>
		<a href="http://www.lpzoo.org/" target="_blank">
			Lincoln Park Zoo

		</a>
	</h5>
	<p>
		A free zoo open year round to the public

	</p>

	<h5>
		<a href="http://www.chicagobikes.org/pdf/lakefront_trail061608.pdf" target="_blank">
			Lakefront Trail
		</a>
	</h5>
	<p>
		Take a walk or run along the lakefront trail or enjoy the beaches, volleyball and tennis courts, and soccer fields with the city scenery in the background. Rent a Divvy bike if you feel like biking along the trail.
	</p>

	<h5>
		<a href="http://www.themagnificentmile.com/" target="_blank">
			The Magnificent Mile
		</a>
	</h5>
	<p>
		Walk the shops along Michigan Ave. north of the river. Stop in to the Signature Room at the John Hancock Center for a cocktail and great view of the city (the cocktails are cheaper than the tickets to the official observatory!)
	</p>

	<h5>
		<a href="http://www.architecture.org/rivercruise" target="_blank">

			Riverboat Cruise
		</a>
	</h5>
	<p>
		Take a riverboat on an architectural tour of the city with the Chicago Architecture Foundation (located in the 1st floor of Natalya’s office at 224 S. Michigan Ave.). Or visit the CAF for a walking tour!

	</p>
	<h5>
		<a href="http://www.choosechicago.com/articles/view/STATE-STREET-SHOPPING/66/" target="_blank">
			State Street Shopping

		</a>
	</h5>
	<p>
		Another great shopping area in the city, be sure to check out the beautiful Tiffany Ceiling inside the 8-story Macy’s (formerly Marshall Field’s)

	</p>


